    {
      "guideline_id": "CMG_3",
      "cmg_number": "3A",
      "source_file": "CMG_3A_RSI__Rapid_Sequence_Intubation_.json",
      "source_title": "RSI (Rapid Sequence Intubation)",
      "text": "##### Type\nDepolarising muscle relaxant [S4]\n\n- **High-risk medication**\n\n##### Presentations\n100mg in 2ml – plastic ampoule\n\n##### Actions\nActs like the neurotransmitter acetylcholine at the neuromuscular junction. Persists for a period long enough to exhaust the motor endplate by prolonged depolarisation.\n\nOnset IV: approx 45 seconds \n Duration IV: 5 – 7 minutes \n\n#### Uses\nTo facilitate airway management in selected patients \n\n#### Adverse Effects\n\n- Bradycardia\n\n- Potassium release\n\n- Increased intraocular and intragastric pressure\n\n- Occasionally, prolonged paralysis\n\n- Has been associated with malignant hyperthermia\n\n#### Contraindications\n\n- Previous reaction to suxamethonium\n\n- Suspected hyperkalaemia\n\n- Use in children\n\n#### Precautions\n\n- Elderly patient\n\n- Neuromuscular disease\n\n- Hypothermic patient\n\n- Fitting patient\n\n- Patient with reversible pathology\n\nSelect patients carefully – always have a fallback position!\n\n#### Pregnancy and Breastfeeding##### Pregnancy\n- Safe to use\n\n##### Breastfeeding\n- Safe to use\n\n#### Doses##### Adult\n- **ICP: **1.5mg/kg IV \n- Over 30 – 60 seconds\n- To a maximum of 150mg.\n\n##### Paediatric\nNot used.\n\n#### Suxamethonium 100mg in 2ml\n- Suxamethonium (applies to 100mg in 2ml): \n- 40kg = 60 mg (1.2 ml)\n- 50kg = 75 mg (1.5 ml)\n- 60kg = 90 mg (1.8 ml)\n- 70kg = 105 mg (2.1 ml)- 80kg = 120 mg (2.4 ml)- 90kg = 135 mg (2.7 ml)- 100kg = 150 mg (3 ml)- **Maximum dose 150 mg**\n#### Special Notes\n- To be used only following completion of the ACTAS designated training programme.\n- If heart rate less than 50/minute, consider atropine prior to suxamethonium.\n- Suxamethonium may cause bradycardia. If patient is bradycardic once ETT is tied in, consider a dose of atropine.\n- **Note:** bradycardia may be a result of a head injury and raised ICP – thus, BP will be elevated. In this case there is no requirement for atropine regardless of the degree of bradycardia.\n- Suxamethonium must be drawn up into a red barrelled syringe.",
